  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](CTR_DRBG ) @text[weight:bold](Key))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](256) @text[weight:bold]( bits))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Internally Generated))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Does not exit ) @text[weight:bold](the module))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](CTR_DRBG Entropy Input))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](384 bits))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Input via API in plaintext))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Does not exit the module))
  }
}
h2[numbered:true](Public Keys)
p(The table below provides a complete list of the Public keys used by the module:)
table[border:all, caption:"Public keys supported"]{
  row[kind:header]{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Public Key Name))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Key Description ))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](ECDSA Verification Key))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](ECDSA) @text[weight:bold]( \(P-224/P-256/P-384/) @text[weight:bold](P-521) @text[weight:bold](\) ) @text[weight:bold](signature) @text[weight:bold]( verification) @text[weight:bold]( key))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](EC DH ) @text[weight:bold](Public Key))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](EC DH \(P-224/P-256/P-384/) @text[weight:bold](P-521) @text[weight:bold](\)) @text[weight:bold]( public key))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](RSA Key \(Key Transport\)))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](RSA \(2048 to 16384 bits\) key encryption \(public key transport\) key))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](RSA Signature Verification Key))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](RSA \(1024 to 16384 bits\) signature verification public key))
  }
}
h2[numbered:true](Key Generation)
p(The module supports generation of ECDSA, EC Diffie-Hellman and RSA key pairs as specified in Section 5 of NIST SP 800-133. The module employs a NIST SP 800-90A random bit generator for creation of the seed for asymmetric key generation. The module requests a minimum number of 128 bits of entropy from its Operational Environment per each call.)
p(The output data path is provided by the data interfaces and is logically disconnected from processes performing key generation or zeroization. No key information will be output through the data output interface when the module zeroizes keys.)
h2[numbered:true](Key Storage)
p("The cryptographic module does not perform persistent storage of keys. Keys and CSPs are passed to the module by the calling application. The keys and CSPs are stored in memory in plaintext. Keys and CSPs residing in internally allocated data structures \\(during the lifetime of an API call\\) can only be accessed using the module defined API. The operating system protects memory and process space from unauthorized access.")
h2[numbered:true](Key Zeroization)
p(The module is passed keys as part of a function call from a calling application and does not store keys persistently. The calling application is responsible for parameters passed in and out of the module. The Operating System and the calling application are responsible to clean up temporary or ephemeral keys.)
pagebreak
h1[numbered:true](Self-tests)
p(FIPS 140-2 requires the module to perform self-tests to ensure the integrity of the module and the correctness of the cryptographic functionality at start up. Some functions require conditional tests during normal operation of the module. The supported tests are listed and described in this section.)
h2[numbered:true](Power-On Self-Tests)
p(Power-on self-tests are run upon the initialization of the module and do not require operator intervention to run. If any of the tests fail, the module will not initialize. The module will enter an error state and no services can be accessed.)
p(The module implements the following power-on self-tests:)
table[border:all, caption:"Power-on Self-tests"]{
  row[kind:header]{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Type))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Test))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Integrity Test))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](HMAC-SHA-512))
  }
  row{
    cell[rowspan:8](@text[weight:bold](Known Answer Test))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](AES KAT \(encryption and decryption. Key size: 128-bits\)))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](AES-GCM KAT \(encryption and decryption. Key size: 128-bits\)))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Triple-DES KAT \(encryption and decryption. Key size: 168-bits\)))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](ECDSA KAT \(signature generation/signature verification. Curve: P-256\) ))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](HMAC KAT \(HMAC-SHA-1, HMAC-SHA-512\)))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](SP 800-90A CTR_DRBG KAT \(Key size: 256-bits\)))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](RSA KAT \(signature generation/signature verification and encryption/decryption. Key size: 2048-bit\)))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](SHA KAT \(SHA-1, SHA-256, SHA-512\)))
  }
}
p(Each module performs all power-on self-tests automatically when the module is initialized. All power-on self-tests must be passed before a User/Crypto Officer can perform services. The Power-on self-tests can be run on demand by power-cycling the host platform.)
h2[numbered:true](Conditional Self-Tests)
p(Conditional self-tests are run during operation of the module.  If any of these tests fail, the module will enter an error state, where no services can be accessed by the operators. The module can be re-initialized to clear the error and resume FIPS mode of operation. Each module performs the following conditional self-tests:)
table[border:all, caption:"Conditional Self-tests"]{
  row[kind:header]{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Type))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Test))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Pair-wise Consistency Test))
    cell{
      p(@text[weight:bold](ECDSA Key P) @text[weight:bold](air generation))
      p(@text[weight:bold](RSA Key Pair generation))
    }
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](CRNGT))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Performed on NDRNG per IG 9.8))
  }
  row{
    cell(@text[weight:bold](DRBG Health Tests))
    cell(@text[weight:bold](Performed on DRBG, per SP 800‐90A Section 11.3. Required per IG C.1. ))
  }
}
p(Pairwise consistency tests are performed for both possible modes of use, e.g. Sign/Verify and Encrypt/Decrypt.)
pagebreak
h1[numbered:true](Mitigation of other Attacks)
p(The module is not designed to mitigate against attacks which are outside of the scope of FIPS 140-2.)
pagebreak
h1[numbered:true](Guidance and Secure Operation)
h2[numbered:true](Installation Instructions)
p(The following steps shall be performed to build, compile and statically link the BoringCrypto module to BoringSSL on the tested Operational Environments. The cryptographic module)
p()
p(The below tools are required in order to build and compile the module:)
p()
p("Clang compiler version 6.0.1 \\(http://releases.llvm.org/download.html\\)")
p("Go programming language version 1.10.3 \\(https://golang.org/dl/\\)")
p("Ninja build system version 1.8.2 \\(https://github.com/ninja-build/ninja/releases\\)")
p()
p(Once the above tools have been obtained, issue the following command to create a CMake toolchain file to specify the use of Clang:)
p()
p("printf \"set\\(CMAKE_C_COMPILER \\\\\"clang\\\\\"\\)\\\\nset\\(CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER \\\\\"clang++\\\\\"\\)\\\\n\" > ${HOME}/toolchain")
p()
p(The FIPS 140-2 validated release of the module can be obtained by downloading the tarball containing the source code at the following location:)
p()
p(https://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/chromium-boringssl-docs/fips/boringssl-66005f41fbc3529ffe8d007708756720529da20d.tar.xz)
p()
p(or by issuing the following command:)
p()
p(wget https://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/chromium-boringssl-docs/fips/boringssl-66005f41fbc3529ffe8d007708756720529da20d.tar.xz)
p()
p(The set of files specified in the archive constitutes the complete set of source files of the validated module. There shall be no additions, deletions, or alterations of this set as used during module build.)
p()
p(The downloaded tarball file can be verified using the below SHA-256 digest value:)
p()
p(b12ad676ee533824f698741bd127f6fbc82c46344398a6d78d25e62c6c418c73)
p()
p(By issuing the following command:)
p()
p(sha256sum boringssl-66005f41fbc3529ffe8d007708756720529da20d.tar.xz)
p()
p(After the tarball has been extracted, the following commands will compile the module:)
p()
p(cd boringssl)
p("mkdir build && cd build && cmake -GNinja -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=${HOME}/toolchain -DFIPS=1 -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release ..")
p(ninja)
p(ninja run_tests)
p()
p(Upon completion of the build process. The module’s status can be verified by issuing:)
p()
p(./tool/bssl isfips)
p()
p(The module will print “1” if it is in a FIPS 140-2 validated mode of operation.)
p()
p()
h2[numbered:true](Secure Operation)
h3[numbered:true](Initialization)
p("The cryptographic module is initialized by loading the module before any cryptographic functionality is available. In User Space the operating system is responsible for the initialization process and loading of the library. The module is designed with a default entry point \\(DEP\\) which ensures that the power-up tests are initiated automatically when the module is loaded.")
h3[numbered:true](Usage of AES OFB, CFB and CFB8)
p(In approved mode, users of the module must not utilize AES OFB, CFB and CFB8.)
h3[numbered:true](Usage of AES-GCM)
p(In the case of AES-GCM, the IV generation method is user selectable and the value can be computed in more than one manner.)
p(Following RFC 5288 for TLS, the module ensures that it's strictly increasing and thus cannot repeat. When the IV exhausts the maximum number of possible values for a given session key, the first party, client or server, to encounter this condition may either trigger a handshake to establish a new encryption key in accordance with RFC 5246, or fail. In either case, the module prevents and IV duplication and thus enforces the security property.)
p(The module’s IV is generated internally by the module’s Approved DRBG. The DRBG seed is generated inside the module’s physical boundary. The IV is 96-bits in length per NIST SP 800-38D, Section 8.2.2 and FIPS 140-2 IG A.5 scenario 2.)
p(The selection of the IV construction method is the responsibility of the user of this cryptographic module. In approved mode, users of the module must not utilize GCM with an externally generated IV.)
p(Per IG A.5, in the event module power is lost and restored the consuming application must ensure that any of its AES-GCM keys used for encryption or decryption are re-distributed.)
h3[numbered:true](Usage of Triple-DES)
p(In accordance with CMVP IG A.13, when operating in a FIPS approved mode of operation, the same Triple-DES key shall not be used to encrypt more than 220 or 216 64-bit data blocks.)
p("The TLS protocol governs the generation of the respective Triple-DES keys. Please refer to IETF RFC 5246 \\(TLS\\) for details relevant to the generation of the individual Triple-DES encryption keys. The user is responsible for ensuring that the module limits the number of encrypted blocks with the same key to no more than 220 when utilized as part of a recognized IETF protocol.")
p(For all other uses of Triple-DES the user is responsible for ensuring that the module limits the number of encrypted blocks with the same key to no more than 216.)
h3[numbered:true](RSA and ECDSA Keys)
p(The module allows the use of 1024 bits RSA keys for legacy purposes including signature generation, which is disallowed to be used in FIPS Approved mode as per NIST SP 800-131A. Therefore, the cryptographic operations with the non-approved key sizes will result in the module operating in non-Approved mode implicitly.)
pagebreak
p(Approved algorithms shall not use the keys generated by the module’s non-Approved key generation methods.)
